# Plan Mode Policy

This rule governs **how plans are produced and closed out** in this repo,
both when Cursor's built-in **Plan mode** is active and when the primary
agent is otherwise authoring a multi-step plan before any writes happen.

It is a companion to `.cursor/rules/subagent-dispatch.mdc` (the general
dispatch policy). When the two rules overlap, this rule wins **inside Plan
mode**; outside Plan mode, the general dispatch policy wins.

> **Scope reminder:** Plan mode is read-only. Every subagent dispatched
> *during* planning must be a read-only / advisory agent (`explorer`,
> `*-architect`, `ui-ux-designer`, reviewers). Write-capable agents
> (`backend-developer`, `frontend-developer`, `refactor-cleaner`) are only
> *referenced* in the plan — they are not dispatched until Plan mode exits
> and the user approves the plan.

---

## 1. The four phases of a Plan

Every non-trivial plan MUST go through these phases, in order:

```
Phase A — Discovery
Phase B — Architect debate
Phase C — UI/UX shaping (if frontend components are involved)
Phase D — Implementation strategy + Closing review checklist
```

Skipping a phase requires a one-sentence justification in the plan itself
(e.g. "Phase C skipped — no UI surface in this change").

---

## 2. Phase A — Discovery (mandatory, parallel reads)

Before any architect is invited to debate, the planner MUST have a concrete
picture of the surface being changed.

- Dispatch `explorer` to map the affected files, modules, current patterns,
  and existing related ADRs / specs.
- If multiple unrelated slices are touched, dispatch **multiple `explorer`
  agents in parallel** (one per slice — Rule R1 of `subagent-dispatch.mdc`).
- Output of this phase is a short "current state" section in the draft plan:
  files in scope, dominant patterns, known debt, and known constraints.

Do not enter Phase B without this.

---

## 3. Phase B — Architect debate (MANDATORY)

> This is the heart of the rule. **A plan in this repo is not allowed to
> reach the user without an architect debate phase.**

For any non-trivial plan you MUST dispatch the relevant `*-architect`
subagent(s) and treat the plan as a **design discussion**, not a checklist.

**Dispatch matrix:**

| Surface touched by the plan | Architect(s) to dispatch | Parallelism |
|---|---|---|
| Server / API / data layer only | `backend-architect` | single |
| Client / UI / app shell only | `frontend-architect` | single |
| Both server and client (full-stack feature) | `backend-architect` ∥ `frontend-architect` | **parallel** |
| Pure infra / tooling / config with no domain shape | architect debate may be skipped — document the reason | n/a |

The architect prompts must be framed as a **debate**, not a request for
sign-off. Each architect is asked, in its dispatch prompt, to:

1. Propose **at least two** viable design options for the plan's subject.
2. List the trade-offs (cost, risk, evolution, performance, a11y where
   relevant) for each option.
3. Recommend one option **with explicit reasoning**, not just preference.
4. Surface any open questions that block a confident decision.

The planner then synthesizes the architects' outputs into the plan's
**"Decisions"** section. If two architects disagree (full-stack case), the
disagreement and its resolution must be written into the plan — it is not
papered over.

Forbidden in Phase B:

- ❌ Authoring the architecture inline without dispatching the architect.
- ❌ Dispatching only one architect when both surfaces are clearly affected.
- ❌ Treating the architect's first option as the answer without recording
  the alternatives that were considered.

---

## 4. Phase C — UI/UX shaping (when frontend components exist)

This phase runs **only after Phase B settles the frontend architecture**
(composition slot, state ownership, data contract). The order is non-
negotiable: architecture first, design second. (Same ordering rule as
§4a in `subagent-dispatch.mdc`.)

### 4.1 When Phase C is required

Trigger Phase C if the plan introduces or substantially redesigns **one or
more frontend components** (new component, new states, new variants, new
responsive behavior, new accessibility model, or new interaction model).

If the only frontend work is a cosmetic tweak (spacing, copy, token swap),
Phase C may be skipped — note this in the plan.

### 4.2 What `ui-ux-designer` produces in Phase C

For each component in scope, the designer must add the following to the plan:

- The **layout direction** and responsive behavior.
- All **visual states**: default / hover / focus / active / disabled /
  loading / empty / error / success.
- The **microcopy** stance (tone, error messages, empty-state CTAs).
- The **motion** stance (duration / easing or "no motion").
- The **WCAG / keyboard / ARIA model** — focus order, roles, live regions,
  contrast targets.
- "**What to watch out for**" notes flagged for the implementer
  (edge cases, locale risks, density risks, RTL, reduced-motion, etc.).

These outputs go into the plan's **"UI/UX direction"** section, indexed per
component, and become the design contract that `frontend-developer` must
implement against in Phase D.

### 4.3 Parallelism rule for `ui-ux-designer` (capped at 2)

`ui-ux-designer` may be parallelized **based on the number of frontend
components in the plan**, with a hard cap:

| Components in the plan | `ui-ux-designer` dispatches |
|---|---|
| 1 component | **1** designer (single dispatch) |
| 2–3 components | **1** designer (handle all in one pass) |
| 4+ components | **2** designers in **parallel**, with the components split into two disjoint, explicit groups |
| Any number | **Never more than 2** designers in parallel |

When parallelizing two designers:

1. Split the components into two **disjoint** groups in the dispatch prompt.
   Each designer owns its group and **must not** spec components outside it.
2. Each designer must use the **same architectural contract** from Phase B
   (same composition slot rules, same state-ownership rules, same data
   contract patterns). Pass that contract verbatim in both dispatch prompts
   so the two designers stay consistent.
3. After both return, the planner reconciles them: shared tokens, shared
   patterns, shared a11y conventions must match across the two outputs. If
   they conflict, the planner resolves in the plan and notes the resolution.

Forbidden in Phase C:

- ❌ Dispatching `ui-ux-designer` **before** Phase B settles the
  architecture (mirrors §4a anti-pattern in `subagent-dispatch.mdc`).
- ❌ Dispatching **3 or more** `ui-ux-designer` agents in parallel.
- ❌ Splitting one component across two designers.
- ❌ Letting either designer redesign the architecture chosen in Phase B.

---

## 5. Phase D — Implementation strategy + Closing review checklist

The plan must finish with two concrete sections that the executing agent
will follow when Plan mode exits.

### 5.1 Implementation strategy (write phase parallelism)

The plan must specify, **per implementation step**, whether it is to be
executed:

- **Sequentially**, or
- **In parallel** with another step.

The default is sequential. Parallel implementation steps may be planned
**only when you are ≥99% confident** that file-set isolation holds — the
five conditions of **Rule W2** in `subagent-dispatch.mdc` must all be true:

1. Discovery (`explorer`) has enumerated the file scope.
2. Each parallel step owns a **disjoint, explicit file allowlist**.
3. No step creates / renames / moves / deletes files outside its allowlist.
4. No step edits a shared config, lockfile, root manifest, barrel/index
   file, schema file, or anything imported by another parallel step.
5. The plan includes the file allowlist for each parallel step verbatim,
   and forbids touching anything else.

If any of the five is uncertain, the plan **must mark the steps sequential**.
Bias to serial — Rule W3 in `subagent-dispatch.mdc`.

Typical safe parallel pairings (when isolation is provable):

- `backend-developer` (server slice X) ∥ `frontend-developer` (client
  slice Y), where X and Y do not share files and do not edit shared
  contracts in the same step.
- Two `frontend-developer` dispatches across two unrelated component
  folders (each with its own allowlist).

If you cannot write the allowlists confidently, **do not plan it as
parallel**. Write it sequentially.

### 5.2 Closing review checklist (MANDATORY)

Every plan MUST end with an explicit **"Closing review"** section that
names the reviewer subagents to dispatch *after* implementation and tells
the executor to dispatch them in **parallel** (Rule R1 in
`subagent-dispatch.mdc`).

Pick reviewers based on what the plan changed:

| The plan changed… | Add this reviewer |
|---|---|
| Any non-trivial code | `code-reviewer` (always) |
| Auth, input handling, secrets, external I/O, MCP/agent surfaces | `security-reviewer` |
| SQL, migrations, indexes, RLS, JSONB, Postgres specifics | `database-reviewer` |
| Module boundaries, integration topology, broad refactor | `architect-reviewer` |
| Frontend component spec / a11y model | `ui-ux-designer` (spec & a11y conformance pass) |

The closing-review section must say, in one line, **which reviewers run in
parallel** at the end. For example:

> **Closing review (parallel):** `code-reviewer` ∥ `security-reviewer` ∥
> `ui-ux-designer` (spec/a11y conformance).

A plan without an explicit closing-review line is incomplete and must be
sent back to Phase D before exiting Plan mode.

### 5.3 Refactor leftover sweep (MANDATORY when refactoring is in scope)

If the plan includes **any refactor work** — extracting a module, renaming
a primitive, consolidating duplicates, removing a pattern, replacing an
abstraction — the closing-review section MUST also include
`refactor-cleaner` to sweep for leftovers:

- Dead code from the old shape (unused exports, orphan files).
- Stale imports and barrel re-exports.
- Outdated comments / TODOs that referred to the removed shape.
- Duplicate copies of code that the refactor was supposed to consolidate.

`refactor-cleaner` runs **after** the implementation steps and **before**
or **in parallel with** the other reviewers — but is itself write-capable,
so it must respect Rule W1 (sequential by default with other writers).

A safe ordering when refactoring is involved:

```
…implementation steps…
   →  refactor-cleaner  (sweep leftovers)
   →  code-reviewer ∥ security-reviewer ∥ architect-reviewer ∥ ui-ux-designer  (parallel)
```

If the plan touches a refactor and **does not** name `refactor-cleaner`, it
is incomplete.

---

## 6. The plan document — required sections

When Plan mode is active, the produced plan must contain these sections, in
this order, so a downstream executor can follow it without guesswork:

1. **Goal** — one paragraph, what we are doing and why.
2. **Current state** — output of Phase A (`explorer` findings).
3. **Decisions** — output of Phase B (`*-architect` debate; options
   considered, option chosen, reasoning, open questions).
4. **UI/UX direction** — output of Phase C (per-component spec from
   `ui-ux-designer`), or a one-line note that Phase C was skipped and why.
5. **Implementation steps** — output of Phase D.1, with each step marked
   *sequential* or *parallel* (with allowlists if parallel).
6. **Closing review** — output of Phase D.2, naming the reviewers that the
   executor must dispatch in parallel after implementation.
7. **Refactor sweep** *(only if refactor is in scope)* — explicit
   `refactor-cleaner` step, placed before the final reviewer fan-out.

A plan that is missing any of sections 1–3, 5, or 6 (and 7 when applicable)
is rejected and must go back through the missing phase.

---

## 7. Quick decision table (Plan mode)

| Situation in Plan mode | Do this |
|---|---|
| Unfamiliar surface | Phase A: parallel `explorer` per slice |
| Pure backend plan | Phase B: `backend-architect` (single) |
| Pure frontend plan, no new components | Phase B: `frontend-architect` (single); Phase C skipped (note in plan) |
| Pure frontend plan, 1–3 new components | Phase B: `frontend-architect` → Phase C: `ui-ux-designer` (single) |
| Pure frontend plan, 4+ new components | Phase B: `frontend-architect` → Phase C: **2× `ui-ux-designer` in parallel** with disjoint component groups |
| Full-stack plan | Phase B: `backend-architect` ∥ `frontend-architect` (parallel); Phase C as above based on component count |
| Plan includes a refactor | Phase D MUST include `refactor-cleaner` before the reviewer fan-out |
| Plan ready to exit Plan mode | Verify §6 — all required sections present, closing-review reviewers named, parallelism explicit |

---

## 8. Anti-patterns specific to Plan mode

- ❌ Producing a plan without a Phase B architect debate ("I just decided
  the design myself").
- ❌ Calling only `frontend-architect` on a clearly full-stack plan, or only
  `backend-architect` on one — both must run in parallel when both surfaces
  move.
- ❌ Dispatching `ui-ux-designer` in Phase C **before** Phase B is settled.
- ❌ Dispatching **3+** `ui-ux-designer` agents in parallel, regardless of
  how many components are in scope.
- ❌ Marking implementation steps as parallel without writing the per-step
  file allowlists into the plan.
- ❌ Closing the plan without an explicit, parallel **Closing review** line.
- ❌ Refactor in the plan, no `refactor-cleaner` step in the closing.
- ❌ Dispatching write-capable agents (`backend-developer`,
  `frontend-developer`, `refactor-cleaner`) **inside** Plan mode. They are
  named in the plan and dispatched only after Plan mode exits.
